.Dd April 22, 2026
.Dt PS 1
.Os
.Sh NAME
.Nm ps
.Nd report process status
.Sh SYNOPSIS
.Nm
.Op Fl aAcdefjHlLmPWyZ
.Op Fl g Ar grplist
.Op Fl h Ar lgrplist
.Op Fl n Ar namelist
.Oo Fl o Ar format Oc Ns ...
.Op Fl p Ar proclist
.Op Fl s Ar sidlist
.Op Fl t Ar term
.Op Fl u Ar uidlist
.Op Fl U Ar uidlist
.Op Fl G Ar gidlist
.Op Fl z Ar zonelist
.Sh DESCRIPTION
The
.Nm
command prints information about active processes.
Without options,
.Nm
prints information about processes that have the same effective user ID and the
same controlling terminal as the invoker.
The output contains only the process ID, terminal identifier, cumulative
execution time, and the command name.
Otherwise, the information that is displayed is controlled by the options.
.Pp
Some options accept lists as arguments.
Items in a list can be either separated by commas or else enclosed in quotes and
separated by commas or spaces.
Values for
.Ar proclist
and
.Ar grplist
must be numeric.
.Pp
The
.Nm
command also accepts BSD-style options
.Pq e.g. aux .
See
.Xr ps 1B .
.Sh OPTIONS
The following options are supported:
.Bl -tag -width Fl
.It Fl a
Lists information about all processes most frequently requested: all those
except session leaders and processes not associated with a terminal.
.Pp
This option is ignored when the
.Fl e
option is also specified.
.It Fl A
Lists information for all processes.
Identical to
.Fl e ,
below.
.It Fl c
Prints information in a format that reflects scheduler properties as described
in
.Xr priocntl 1 .
The
.Fl c
option affects the output of the
.Fl f
and
.Fl l
options, as described below.
.It Fl d
Lists information about all processes except session leaders.
.It Fl e
Lists information about every process now running.
.Pp
When the
.Fl e
option is specified, options
.Fl z ,
.Fl t ,
.Fl u ,
.Fl U ,
.Fl g ,
.Fl G ,
.Fl p ,
.Fl h ,
.Fl s ,
and
.Fl a
have no effect.
.It Fl f
Generates a full listing.
.Pq See below for significance of columns in a full listing.
.It Fl g Ar grplist
Lists only process data whose group leader's ID number(s) appears in
.Ar grplist .
.Po
A group leader is a process whose process ID number is identical to its process
group ID number.
.Pc
.Pp
This option is ignored when the
.Fl e
option is also specified.
.It Fl G Ar gidlist
Lists information for processes whose real group ID numbers are given in
.Ar gidlist .
The
.Ar gidlist
must be a single argument in the form of a blank- or comma-separated list.
.Pp
This option is ignored when the
.Fl e
option is also specified.
.It Fl h Ar lgrplist
Lists only the processes homed to the specified
.Ar lgrplist .
Nothing is listed for any invalid group specified in
.Ar lgrplist .
.Pp
This option is ignored when the
.Fl e
option is also specified.
.It Fl H
Prints the home lgroup of the process under an additional column header,
.Sy LGRP .
.It Fl j
Prints session ID and process group ID.
.It Fl l
Generates a long listing.
.Pq See below .
.It Fl L
Prints information about each light weight process
.Pq lwp
in each selected process.
.Pq See below .
.It Fl m
Prints microstate information about the process or, when
.Fl L
is specified, each thread.
See below for a list of the output fields this adds.
.It Fl n Ar namelist
Specifies the name of an alternative system
.Ar namelist
file in place of the default.
This option is accepted for compatibility, but is ignored.
.It Fl o Ar format
Prints information according to the format specification given in
.Ar format .
This is fully described in
.Sx DISPLAY FORMATS .
Multiple
.Fl o
options can
be specified; the format specification is interpreted as the
space-character-separated concatenation of all the
.Ar format
option-arguments.
.It Fl p Ar proclist
Lists only process data whose process ID numbers are given in
.Ar proclist .
.Pp
This option is ignored when the
.Fl e
option is also specified.
.It Fl P
Prints the number of the processor to which the process or lwp is bound, if
any, under an additional column header,
.Sy PSR .
.It Fl s Ar sidlist
Lists information on all session leaders whose IDs appear in
.Ar sidlist .
.Pp
This option is ignored when the
.Fl e
option is also specified.
.It Fl t Ar term
Lists only process data associated with
.Ar term .
Terminal identifiers are specified as a device file name, and an identifier.
For example,
.Sy term/a ,
or
.Sy pts/0 .
.Pp
This option is ignored when the
.Fl e
option is also specified.
.It Fl u Ar uidlist
Lists only process data whose effective user ID number or login name is given in
.Ar uidlist .
In the listing, the numerical user ID is printed unless you give the
.Fl f
option, which prints the login name.
.Pp
This option is ignored when the
.Fl e
option is also specified.
.It Fl U Ar uidlist
Lists information for processes whose real user ID numbers or login names are
given in
.Ar uidlist .
The
.Ar uidlist
must be a single argument in the form of a blank- or comma-separated list.
.Pp
This option is ignored when the
.Fl e
option is also specified.
.It Fl W
Truncate long names even when
.Nm
would normally print them in full.
A trailing asterisk marks a long name that has been truncated to fit the column.
.It Fl y
Under a long listing
.Pq Fl l ,
omits the obsolete
.Sy F
and
.Sy ADDR
columns and includes an
.Sy RSS
column to report the resident set size of the process.
Under the
.Fl y
option, both
.Sy RSS
and
.Sy SZ
.Pq see below
is reported in units of kilobytes instead of pages.
.It Fl z Ar zonelist
Lists only processes in the specified zones.
Zones can be specified either by name or ID.
This option is only useful when executed in the global zone.
.Pp
This option is ignored when the
.Fl e
option is also specified.
.It Fl Z
Prints the name of the zone with which the process is associated under an
additional column header,
.Sy ZONE .
The
.Sy ZONE
column width is limited to 8 characters.
Use
.Nm Fl eZ
for a quick way to see information about every process now running along with
the associated zone name.
Use
.Bd -literal -offset 2n
ps -eo zone,uid,pid,ppid,time,comm,...
.Ed
.Pp
to see zone names wider than 8 characters.
.El
.Pp
Many of the options shown are used to select processes to list.
If any are specified, the default list is ignored and
.Nm
selects the processes represented by the inclusive OR of all the
selection-criteria options.
.Sh DISPLAY FORMATS
Under the
.Fl f
option,
.Nm
tries to determine the command name and arguments given when the process was
created by examining the user block.
Failing this, the command name is printed, as it would have appeared without the
.Fl f
option, in square brackets.
.Pp
The column headings and the meaning of the columns in a
.Nm
listing are given below; the letters
.Sy f
and
.Sy l
indicate the option
.Pq full or long, respectively
that causes the corresponding heading to appear;
.Sy all
means that the heading always appears.
Note: These two options determine only what information is provided for a
process; they do not determine which processes are listed.
.Bl -tag -width Ds
.It Sy F (l)
Flags
.Pq hexadecimal and additive
associated with the process.
These flags are available for historical purposes; no meaning should be
currently ascribed to them.
.It Sy S (l)
The state of the process:
.Bl -tag -width Ds
.It Sy O
Process is running on a processor.
.It Sy S
Sleeping: process is waiting for an event to complete.
.It Sy R
Runnable: process is on run queue.
.It Sy T
Process is stopped, either by a job control signal or because it is being
traced.
.It Sy W
Waiting: process is waiting for CPU usage to drop to the CPU-caps enforced
limits.
.It Sy Z
Zombie state: process terminated and parent not waiting.
.El
.It Sy UID (f,l)
The effective user ID number of the process
.Po
the login name is printed under the
.Fl f
option
.Pc .
A trailing asterisk marks a long name that has been truncated to fit the column.
.It Sy PID (all)
The process ID of the process
.Pq this datum is necessary in order to kill a process.
.It Sy PPID (f,l)
The process ID of the parent process.
.It Sy C (f,l)
Processor utilization for scheduling
.Pq obsolete .
Not printed when the
.Fl c
option is used.
.It Sy CLS (f,l)
Scheduling class.
Printed only when the
.Fl c
option is used.
.It Sy PRI (l)
The priority of the process.
Without the
.Fl c
option, higher numbers mean lower priority.
With the
.Fl c
option, higher numbers mean higher priority.
.It Sy NI (l)
Nice value, used in priority computation.
Not printed when the
.Fl c
option is used.
Only processes in the certain scheduling classes have a nice value.
.It Sy ADDR (l)
The memory address of the process.
.It Sy SZ (l)
The total size of the process in virtual memory, including all mapped files and
devices, in pages.
See
.Xr pagesize 1 .
.It Sy WCHAN (l)
The address of an event for which the process is sleeping
.Pq if blank, the process is running .
.It Sy STIME (f)
The starting time of the process, given in hours, minutes, and seconds.
.Po
A process begun more than twenty-four hours before the
.Nm ps
inquiry is executed is given in months and days.
.Pc
.It Sy TTY (all)
The controlling terminal for the process
.Po
the message,
.Sy \&? ,
is printed when there is no controlling terminal
.Pc .
.It Sy TIME (all)
The cumulative execution time for the process.
.It Sy LTIME (all)
The execution time for the lwp being reported.
.It Sy CMD (all)
The command name
.Po
the full command name and its arguments, up to a limit of 80 characters, are
printed under the
.Fl f
option
.Pc .
.El
.Pp
The following two additional columns are printed when the
.Fl j
option is specified:
.Bl -tag -width Ds
.It Sy PGID
The process ID of the process group leader.
.It Sy SID
The process ID of the session leader.
.El
.Pp
The following two additional columns are printed when the
.Fl L
option is specified:
.Bl -tag -width Ds
.It Sy LWP
The lwp ID of the lwp being reported.
.It Sy NLWP
The number of lwps in the process
.Po
if
.Fl f
is also specified
.Pc .
.El
.Pp
Under the
.Fl L
option, one line is printed for each lwp in the process and the time-reporting
fields
.Sy STIME
and
.Sy LTIME
show the values for the lwp, not the process.
A traditional single-threaded process contains only one lwp.
.Pp
The
.Fl m
option prints information about the process or thread microstate accounting.
When looking at information for a process, it is a summation across all threads
that currently exist or have ever existed in the process.
Use the
.Fl o
option for stable output.
Stable output for these fields is printed as a hexadecimal number of
nanoseconds.
Otherwise, times are humanized and are displayed in the following units:
.Bl -tag -compact -width Ds -offset indent
.It Sy ns
nanoseconds
.It Sy us
microseconds
.It Sy ms
milliseconds
.It Sy s
seconds
.It Sy m
minutes
.It Sy h
hours
.It Sy d
days
.It Sy y
years
.El
.Pp
The following additional columns are printed when the
.Fl m
option is specified:
.Bl -tag -width Ds
.It Sy USERTIME
Elapsed time spent in user mode.
.It Sy SYSTIME
Elapsed time spent in system mode.
Generally due to executing system calls or page faults.
.It Sy TTIME
Time spent in other system traps.
.It Sy TFTIME
Time spent asleep in user text page faults.
.It Sy DFTIME
Time spent asleep in user data page faults.
.It Sy KFTIME
Time spent asleep in kernel page faults.
.It Sy LTIME
Time spent asleep waiting for a user-mode lock.
.It Sy SLPTIME
Time spent asleep for any other reason.
.It Sy WTIME
Time spent runnable, but waiting for CPU availability.
.It Sy STOPTIME
Time spent stopped for any reason, such as job control, use of
.Pa /proc ,
etc.
.El
.Pp
A process that has exited and has a parent, but has not yet been waited for by
the parent, is marked
.Sy <defunct> .
.Ss Fl o No format
The
.Fl o
option allows the output format to be specified under user control.
.Pp
The format specification must be a list of names presented as a single
argument, blank- or comma-separated.
Each variable has a default header.
The default header can be overridden by appending an equals sign and the new
text of the header.
The rest of the characters in the argument is used as the header text.
The fields specified are written in the order specified on the command line, and
should be arranged in columns in the output.
The field widths are selected by the system to be at least as wide as the header
text
.Pq default or overridden value .
If the header text is null, such as
.Fl o Ar user=
the field width is at least as wide as the default header text.
Long names are not truncated in this mode.
If all header text fields are null, no header line is written.
.Pp
The following names are recognized in the POSIX locale:
.Bl -tag -width Ds
.It Sy user
The effective user ID of the process.
This is the textual user ID, if it can be obtained and the field width permits,
or a decimal representation otherwise.
.It Sy ruser
The real user ID of the process.
This is the textual user ID, if it can be obtained and the field width permits,
or a decimal representation otherwise.
.It Sy group
The effective group ID of the process.
This is the textual group ID, if it can be obtained and the field width permits,
or a decimal representation otherwise.
.It Sy rgroup
The real group ID of the process.
This is the textual group ID, if it can be obtained and the field width permits,
or a decimal representation otherwise.
.It Sy pid
The decimal value of the process ID.
.It Sy ppid
The decimal value of the parent process ID.
.It Sy pgid
The decimal value of the process group ID.
.It Sy pcpu
The ratio of CPU time used recently to CPU time available in the same period,
expressed as a percentage.
The meaning of
.Sq recently
in this context is unspecified.
The CPU time available is determined in an unspecified manner.
.It Sy vsz
The total size of the process in virtual memory, in kilobytes.
.It Sy nice
The decimal value of the system scheduling priority of the process.
See
.Xr nice 1 .
.It Sy etime
In the POSIX locale, the elapsed time since the process was started, in the
form:
.Pp
[[dd-]hh:]mm:ss
.Pp
where
.Bl -tag -width Ds
.It Em dd
is the number of days
.It Em hh
is the number of hours
.It Em mm
is the number of minutes
.It Em ss
is the number of seconds
.El
.Pp
The
.Em dd
field is a decimal integer.
The
.Em hh ,
.Em mm ,
and
.Em ss
fields are two-digit decimal integers padded on the left with zeros.
.It Sy time
In the POSIX locale, the cumulative CPU time of the process in the form:
.Pp
[dd-]hh:mm:ss
.Pp
The
.Em dd ,
.Em hh ,
.Em mm ,
and
.Em ss
fields are as described in the
.Sy etime
specifier.
.It Sy tty
The name of the controlling terminal of the process (if any) in the same format
used by the
.Xr who 1
command.
.It Sy comm
The name of the command being executed
.Pq argv[0] value
as a string.
.It Sy args
The command with all its arguments as a string.
The implementation might truncate this value to the field width; it is
implementation-dependent whether any further truncation occurs.
It is unspecified whether the string represented is a version of the argument
list as it was passed to the command when it started, or is a version of the
arguments as they might have been modified by the application.
Applications cannot depend on being able to modify their argument list and
having that modification be reflected in the output of
.Nm .
The illumos implementation limits the string to 80 bytes; the string is the
version of the argument list as it was passed to the command when it started.
.El
.Pp
The following names are recognized in the illumos implementation:
.Bl -tag -width Ds
.It Sy f
Flags
.Pq hexadecimal and additive
associated with the process.
.It Sy s
The state of the process.
.It Sy c
Processor utilization for scheduling
.Pq obsolete .
.It Sy uid
The effective user ID number of the process as a decimal integer.
.It Sy ruid
The real user ID number of the process as a decimal integer.
.It Sy gid
The effective group ID number of the process as a decimal integer.
.It Sy rgid
The real group ID number of the process as a decimal integer.
.It Sy projid
The project ID number of the process as a decimal integer.
.It Sy project
The project ID of the process as a textual value if that value can be obtained;
otherwise, as a decimal integer.
.It Sy zoneid
The zone ID number of the process as a decimal integer.
.It Sy zone
The zone ID of the process as a textual value if that value can be obtained;
otherwise, as a decimal integer.
.It Sy sid
The process ID of the session leader.
.It Sy taskid
The task ID of the process.
.It Sy class
The scheduling class of the process.
.It Sy pri
The priority of the process.
Higher numbers mean higher priority.
.It Sy opri
The obsolete priority of the process.
Lower numbers mean higher priority.
.It Sy lwp
The decimal value of the lwp ID.
Requesting this formatting option causes one line to be printed for each lwp in
the process.
.It Sy lwpname
The name of the lwp, if set.
Requesting this formatting option causes one line to be printed for each lwp in
the process.
.It Sy nlwp
The number of lwps in the process.
.It Sy psr
The number of the processor to which the process or lwp is bound.
.It Sy pset
The ID of the processor set to which the process or lwp is bound.
.It Sy addr
The memory address of the process.
.It Sy osz
The total size of the process in virtual memory, in pages.
.It Sy wchan
The address of an event for which the process is sleeping
.Pq if -1, the process is running .
.It Sy stime
The starting time or date of the process, printed with no blanks.
.It Sy rss
The resident set size of the process, in kilobytes.
The
.Sy rss
value reported by
.Nm ps
is an estimate provided by
.Xr proc 5
that might underestimate the actual resident set size.
Users who wish to get more accurate usage information for capacity planning
should use
.Xr pmap 1
.Fl x
instead.
.It Sy pmem
The ratio of the process's resident set size to the physical memory on the
machine, expressed as a percentage.
.It Sy fname
The first 8 bytes of the base name of the process's executable file.
.It Sy ctid
The contract ID of the process contract the process is a member of as a decimal
integer.
.It Sy lgrp
The home lgroup of the process.
.It Sy dmodel
The data model of the process, printed in the same manner as via
.Xr pflags 1 .
The currently supported data models are _ILP32 and _LP64.
.It Sy usertime
Elapsed time executing in user mode.
.It Sy systime
Elapsed time executing in system mode.
Generally due to executing system calls or page faults.
.It Sy ttime
Time spent in other system traps.
.It Sy tftime
Time spent asleep in user text page faults.
.It Sy dftime
Time spent asleep in user data page faults.
.It Sy kftime
Time spent asleep in kernel page faults.
.It Sy ltime
Time spent asleep waiting for a user-mode lock.
.It Sy slptime
Time spent asleep for any other reason.
.It Sy wtime
Time spent runnable, but waiting for CPU availability.
.It Sy stoptime
Time spent stopped for any reason, such as job control, use of
.Pa /proc ,
etc.
.It Sy minf
Number of minor page faults.
.It Sy majf
Number of major page faults.
.It Sy vctx
Count of voluntary context switches.
.It Sy ictx
Count of involuntary context switches.
.It Sy sigs
Count of signals received.
.It Sy sysc
Count of system calls executed.
.El
.Pp
Only
.Sy comm ,
.Sy lwpname ,
and
.Sy args
are allowed to contain blank
characters; all others, including the illumos implementation variables, are not.
.Pp
